    <stitle>BE 200 BUS FRONT END AND BODY COMPONENTS - Description - Front End</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="20">
        <title>Front End</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <para>The BE 200 Series school bus chassis is a conventional type chassis, with front engine, front hood
                fenders and bumper. The BE model chassis is manufactured for the complete BE series bus application by
                the IC Corporation, a wholly owned subsidiary of International Truck and Engine Corporation.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700607" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700607.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="392px"
                         scalefitheight="368px"/>
                <caption>Figure 7. Front End</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. FRONT HOOD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. PASSENGER SIDE EXTERIOR MOUNTED REAR VIEW MIRROR</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. SCHOOL BUS FRONT WARNING LIGHTS</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. FRONT SCHOOL BUS IDENTIFICATION PANEL</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. DRIVER SIDE EXTERIOR MOUNTED REAR VIEW MIRROR</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. ENGINE AIR INLET ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>7. FRONT FENDER ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>8. FRONT WHEEL MUD FLAPS</callout1>
                    <callout1>9. HEADLIGHT AND DIRECTIONAL ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>10. GRILLE AND SHROUD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>11. FRONT BUMPER ASSEMBLY WITH SAFETY GATE</callout1>
                    <callout1>12. SAFETY GATE</callout1>
                    <callout1>13. CROSS VIEW MIRRORS</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Bumper</title>
            <para>The front bumper is a one piece aerodynamically styled steel bumper. The bumper incorporates a swing
                out safety gate for passenger protection when entering or leaving the passenger compartment
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700608" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700608.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 8. Front Bumper</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Hood</title>
            <para>The fiberglass hood is a sculptured, three-piece hood with bonded fenders, and removable valance
                sections. The hood is a tilting type. The narrowed, streamlined, tilting, fiberglass hoods provide
                aerodynamics (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700609">Figure 9</hotlnk>) and functional design styling, while still enclosing the
                air cleaner.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700609" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700609.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="352px"/>
                <caption>Figure 9. BE 200 Series Hood Assembly</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. BE HOOD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. AIR INTAKE OPENINGS AND GRILLE</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. HOOD LATCH MOUNTING</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. FENDER ASSEMBLY (BONDED TO HOOD)</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. HEADLIGHT ASSEMBLY HOUSING</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. HOOD HINGE AND CROSS BAR</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Grille</title>
            <para>The grille and grille shroud assembly on the BE Series model is a single removable component. The
                assembly is attached to the hood assembly with mounting screws and insert mounting tabs. The BE Series
                bus chassis has an additional composite application which encapsulates the IC Corporation identification
                badge.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700610" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700610.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="240px"
                         scalefitheight="248px"/>
                <caption>Figure 10. BE Series Grille Assembly</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. IC CORPORATION LOGO BADGE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. SHROUD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. GRILLE</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Splash Panels</title>
            <para>The splash panels on the BE Series bus model minimize splash and mud, protecting vital engine systems
                from corrosion and malfunction (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700611">Figure 11</hotlnk>
                and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700612">Figure 12</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700611" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700611.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="280px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 11. BE Series Hood Splash Panel (Passenger Side Shown)</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. HOOD</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. MOLDED AIR INTAKE ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. SPLASH PANEL ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f4700612" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700612.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 12. BE Series Splash Panel (Driver Side Shown)</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. SPLASH PANEL (DRIVER SIDE)</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. SPLASH PANEL MOUNTING SCREWS</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. GRILLE ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. HINGE CROSSBAR</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. RADIATOR TOP FRAME</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. HOOD STOP CABLE BRACKET</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Fenders</title>
            <para>The fenders on the BE Series are part of the three-piece bonded tilt type fiberglass hood assembly
                with bolt on removable valance sections that surround the headlight housings (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700613">Figure 13</hotlnk>). All fender assemblies have fender extensions which are
                mounted to the lower forward cowl structure.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700613" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700613.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 13. BE Series Fender Assembly</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. HOOD AIR INLET FRAME AND GRILLE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. FENDER SECTION</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. HEADLIGHT HOUSING</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Air Intakes</title>
            <para>On the BE series, air is taken in at the vent located on the driver side section of the hood assembly,
                forward of the chassis cowl assembly. The intake air is routed through molded duct work bonded to the
                underside of the hood assembly and routed to the air cleaner.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700614" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700614.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 14. BE Series Air Intake</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. AIR INTAKE HOOD FRAME</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. HOOD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. INTAKE GRILL MOUNTING SCREWS</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. INTAKE GRILLE ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Fender Extensions</title>
            <para>Fender extensions are an integral part of the fender system on the BE series bus chassis. The fender
                extensions have been designed to provide splash and spray protection. This protects the lower front of
                the cowl from splash and road debris kicked up by the front tires, and it also keeps the entry door and
                step cleaner (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700615">Figure 15</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700615" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700615.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 15. BE Series Fender Extension (Driver Side Shown)</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. HOOD SEAL</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. COWL ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. MUD GUARD</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. FENDER EXTENSION</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. HOOD STOP</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Fender Valance Panels</title>
            <para>The fender valance panel (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700616">Figure 16</hotlnk>) is a fiberglass bolt-on assembly which attaches to the
                fender assembly and encapsulates the headlight housing and assembly. The valance panels are removable
                panels.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700616" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700616.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 16. Valance Panels</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. VALANCE MOUNTING HOLES</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. VALANCE PANEL (DRIVER SIDE SHOWN)</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Mud Guards</title>
            <para>The mud guards (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700617">Figure 17, Item 1</hotlnk>) on the BE Series chassis are located at the bottom
                of the fender extension assembly on each side of the chassis. The mud guards help minimize the damage to
                the lower edge of the cowl and body components, including the passenger entry door and step.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700617" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700617.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="288px"/>
                <caption>Figure 17. Mud Guards</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. MUD GUARD</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. MUD GUARD REINFORCING BAR</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Headlight Assemblies</title>
            <para>The headlight assemblies (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700618">Figure 18, Item 4</hotlnk>) are mounted in the forward fender section within a
                molded housing unit, and are part of the fender assembly. The valance panels encapsulate the headlight
                assembly. The headlight assembly combines the required reflector and direction light as well as the
                halogen headlight bulb.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700618" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700618.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="248px"/>
                <caption>Figure 18. Headlight Assembly</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. CROSS-VIEW MIRROR MOUNTING BASE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. HOOD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. GRILLE ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. HEADLIGHT AND DIRECTIONAL ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. BUMPER ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. VALANCE PANEL</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Hood Seal</title>
            <para>The hood seal (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700619">Figure 19, Item 1</hotlnk>) is located on the leading edge of the hood support
                assembly. The hood support assembly is located on the upper cowl assembly, below the body windshield.
                The cowl/hood seal on the BE series model is a one piece seal.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700619" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700619.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="264px"
                         scalefitheight="208px"/>
                <caption>Figure 19. Cowl/Hood Seal</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. HOOD / COWL SEAL</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. UPPER COWL SECTION</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Engine Cowl</title>
            <para>The engine cowl assembly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700620">Figure 20, Item 1</hotlnk>) is located forward of the bus body module. The
                cowl assembly supports the hood assembly, electrical harness connections, brake, accelerator and
                steering mounting points. The engine cowl supports the hood latch mechanism, the hood stop and
                adjustment bracket and fender extension mounting points.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700620" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700620.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 20. Engine Cowl Assembly</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. COWL ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. DRIVER SIDE FENDER EXTENSION</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. PASSENGER SIDE FENDER EXTENSION</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Hood Latch</title>
            <para>The hood latch assemblies (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700621">Figure 21</hotlnk>) are located at each side of the cowl. The latching
                assembly secures the hood in its properly closed position. The locking portion or clip section is
                located on the cowl. The locking arm and connecting point are located on the side section of the hood
                assembly.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700621" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700621.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 21. Hood Latch Assembly (Passenger Side Shown)</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. HOOD LATCHING CLIP</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. COWL</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. LATCHING ARM BASE</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. HOOD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. FENDER EXTENSION</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Windshield Washer Fluid Reservoir</title>
            <para>The windshield washer fluid reservoir (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700622">Figure 22, Item 2</hotlnk>) on the BE chassis is located on the right frame
                rail, outboard of the radiator mounting bushing. The windshield fluid reservoir is mounted on a bracket
                attached to the frame rail. The reservoir pump and harness connection are part of the hood harness
                assembly.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700622" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700622.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="288px"
                         scalefitheight="288px"/>
                <caption>Figure 22. Windshield Washer Fluid Reservoir</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. RESERVOIR FILL CAP</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. WASHER FLUID RESERVOIR</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. WASHER FLUID PUMP</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. WINDSHIELD WASHER FLUID SUPPLY HOSE</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. RESERVOIR MOUNTING BOLTS</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. RESERVOIR MOUNTING BRACKET</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Safety Gate</title>
            <para>The Safety gate or arm (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700623">Figure 23, Item 2</hotlnk>) is an integral part of the bumper assembly and
                designed to direct the flow of the students around the front of the bus in full view of the driver. The
                safety gate swings out in a perpendicular direction to the bumper assembly approximately 80 inches.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700623" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700623.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 23. Safety Gate / Arm</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. GRILLE AND SHROUD ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. SAFETY GATE</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. BUMPER ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Lollipop Style Fender Mounter Directional Lights (Optional)</title>
            <para>The Lollipop style, fender-mounted directional lights (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700624">Figure 24, Item 3</hotlnk>) are an optional front directional assembly located
                on the top of the fender assembly.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700624" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700624.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="248px"/>
                <caption>Figure 24. Lollipop Directional Lights</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. AIR INTAKE FRAME</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. HOOD</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. LOLLIPOP DIRECTIONAL LIGHT</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. DIRECTIONAL LIGHT FENDER MOUNTING BASE</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Cross-View Fender Mounted Mirrors</title>
            <para>The cross-view fender-mounted mirrors (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700625">Figure 25</hotlnk>) are convex-styled mirrors located on the forward front
                fender sections of the front end assembly. These mirrors allow a cross-view field of vision for the bus
                operator during pick up and discharge of passengers.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700625" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700625.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="288px"/>
                <caption>Figure 25. Typical Cross-View Mirror Assemblies</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Hood Stop Assembly</title>
            <para>The hood stop assembly (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700626">Figure 26</hotlnk>) is mounted each side of the cowl. The hood stop allows the
                hood to rest at a certain designed height to allow clearance for the components under the hood. The hood
                stop bushing is also designed to aid in the ease of operation in tilting the hood.
            </para>
            <figure id="f4700626" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg47/G4700626.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="224px"/>
                <caption>Figure 26. Hood Stop</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. HOOD STOP NYLON BUSHING</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. COWL ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. HOOD STOP MOUNTING BRACKET</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
